-- ── TIER 0: Core concepts ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

('economic_buyer',
 'The Economic Buyer',
 'The Economic Buyer is the person who can say yes when everyone else has said no — and no when everyone else has said yes. They control the budget and are ultimately accountable for the decision. Most technical founders never meet them.',
 E'## The Economic Buyer\n\nIn any enterprise deal, there is one person whose approval is necessary and sufficient for the purchase to happen. This is the Economic Buyer (EB). They have three defining characteristics:\n\n1. **Budget authority** — they can release funds without seeking approval from anyone above them for this purchase\n2. **Organisational accountability** — they are measured on the outcome the product is meant to deliver\n3. **Final word** — their yes closes the deal; their no kills it regardless of how enthusiastic everyone else is\n\nThe EB is rarely the person who found you, contacted you, or invited you to demo. That person is usually a technical evaluator, an internal champion, or a functional buyer. They are valuable — but they are not the EB.\n\n### Why technical founders avoid the EB\n\nMeeting the EB is uncomfortable for two reasons. First, they are typically senior and time-scarce — getting the meeting feels presumptuous. Second, they are not technical, so the conversation has to be about business outcomes rather than product features. Technical founders are confident talking about features. They are less confident talking about ROI, competitive position, or organisational risk.\n\nThe avoidance is understandable. It is also the single most common reason enterprise deals stall.\n\n### What happens when you skip the EB\n\nYou do a great technical evaluation. Your champion is enthusiastic. You write a proposal. Weeks pass. The champion says "we''re still working through the internal process." More weeks pass. Eventually you discover that the EB looked at the budget line, asked one question nobody could answer, and quietly deprioritised the initiative. You were never in the room.\n\n### How to get to the EB\n\nYou rarely get to the EB directly. You get there through your champion. The question to ask your champion is: "If we build a business case together, who would you present it to for final approval?" This identifies the EB without the awkwardness of asking "who controls the budget?" Listen carefully to the answer — sometimes the champion names someone and then adds "but they''ll just rubber-stamp whatever I recommend," which tells you the champion has overstated their authority.',
 'If you needed to get purchase approval by the end of this quarter, who would you need to convince — and have we met them?',
 'The deal has been in "qualifying" or "proposing" for 30+ days and the founder has only ever spoken to technical contacts. When asked who approves the budget, the champion says "I handle that" without naming a specific person or process.',
 'The founder has a direct relationship with the EB — not necessarily close, but the EB knows who Salient is, has seen the business case framing, and has asked at least one substantive question. The champion has confirmed the EB is the right person.',
 'A founder spent four months working with an AI engineer at a mid-size financial services firm. The evaluation was thorough; the engineer loved the product. When they submitted the proposal, the CFO — who had never been mentioned — rejected it in a single email. The reason: the initiative had not been connected to any of the CFO''s three stated priorities for the year. The founder had been selling to someone who had no authority to buy.',
 0, 10),

('economic_buyer_met',
 'Meeting the Economic Buyer',
 'There is a meaningful difference between knowing who the Economic Buyer is and having actually met them. Until you have had a direct conversation, you are relying on your champion''s interpretation of the EB''s position — which is often more optimistic than reality.',
 E'## Meeting the Economic Buyer\n\nOnce you know who the Economic Buyer is, the next milestone is getting in front of them directly. This is not about a formal pitch — it can be a 15-minute introductory call. The goal is to establish a direct relationship so that when your champion takes the business case to the EB, the EB has a face and a conversation to attach to it.\n\n### Why "I''ll pass it on" is not enough\n\nWhen you ask your champion to take your business case to the EB, the champion will do their best — but they will interpret your case through their own lens, answer questions you have never heard, and be unable to respond to objections they did not anticipate. A champion who has never arranged an EB introduction is also signalling something about their own influence: they may not have the standing to get you in the room.\n\n### What to say to get the meeting\n\nAsk your champion: "I want to make sure I''m not wasting [EB name]''s time when this gets to them. Would it make sense for me to spend 15 minutes with them to understand their priorities, so I can make sure our proposal is framed correctly?" This frames the meeting as serving the EB, not pitching to them.\n\n### What to do in the EB meeting\n\nDo not demo. Do not pitch. Ask three questions:\n1. What are the one or two outcomes your organisation is most focused on this year?\n2. What would make this initiative a clear success from your perspective?\n3. What would need to be true for this to move forward on the timeline we''ve discussed?\n\nListen. Take notes. Frame everything you do afterward around what you heard.',
 'Would it make sense for us to spend 15 minutes with [EB name] before we write the proposal — so we can make sure it''s framed around their priorities rather than ours?',
 'The founder has been told "don''t worry about getting to them, I''ll handle that internally." The deal has reached Proposing without any direct EB contact. The champion reports EB reactions second-hand.',
 'The founder has had at least one direct conversation with the EB. The EB has asked at least one substantive question about outcomes or risk. The champion is aware the founder and EB have a direct relationship.',
 'A founder was told by their champion that the CTO "was fully on board." The proposal went up, and two weeks later the champion reported that the CTO wanted to "revisit the scope." In a call that the founder finally managed to arrange directly with the CTO, it emerged that the CTO had never seen the full proposal — the champion had summarised it verbally, got a non-committal response, and reported it as agreement. Fifteen minutes with the CTO directly would have caught this in week one.',
 0, 20),

('pain',
 'Identified Pain',
 'Pain is the business problem the Economic Buyer is accountable for solving. Not a technical inconvenience, not a nice-to-have improvement — a problem that has a cost if it goes unsolved. Until you can state the pain in one sentence that the EB would recognise and agree with, you do not have identified pain.',
 E'## Identified Pain\n\nEvery enterprise purchase exists because something is broken, expensive, slow, or risky — and someone is accountable for fixing it. That is the pain. Your job is to identify it with enough precision that the Economic Buyer would read your one-sentence description and say "yes, that is exactly the problem."\n\n### The pain hierarchy\n\nNot all pain is equal. Pain that comes with a number attached ("this costs us £2M per year in engineering time") is more actionable than pain that is qualitative ("our process is inefficient"). Pain that the EB is personally accountable for is more powerful than pain that sits in a department the EB funds but does not own.\n\nThe strongest version of identified pain: "You are spending £X on Y, it takes Z time, and it is blocking W strategic initiative."\n\n### Technical pain vs. business pain\n\nTechnical founders naturally identify technical pain — the API is slow, the model is inaccurate, the integration is fragile. This is real, but it is not sufficient for an EB-level conversation. Technical pain needs to be translated: what does the slow API cost in engineer-hours per quarter? What does the inaccurate model cost in manual review time or customer churn?\n\n### Why pain must be confirmed by the EB, not inferred\n\nYour champion may describe pain with genuine conviction. But the champion''s pain and the EB''s pain are not always the same thing. The champion cares about engineering velocity; the EB cares about hitting a revenue target. Your champion''s pain may be real and important to them while being invisible on the EB''s dashboard.\n\nPain is only properly identified when you have heard the EB describe it in their own words.',
 'What happens to your organisation if this problem is not solved in the next 12 months — and what is the cost of that?',
 'The pain is described in product terms ("they need better data quality") rather than business terms. The founder cannot quantify the cost of the problem. The pain was articulated by the champion but has never been confirmed with the EB.',
 'The pain is stated in business terms with a number: "Their data quality issues are costing approximately £800k/year in manual reconciliation, and the CFO has identified this as a top-three operational priority." The EB has used this language themselves, unprompted.',
 'A founder built an entire proposal around "improving model inference speed by 40%." The proposal went to the EB, who responded that inference speed was not a current priority — their engineering team had plenty of capacity. The real pain, which the founder had never uncovered, was that the EB needed to show the board a reduction in third-party API costs. The product could have solved that problem too, but nobody had ever framed it that way.',
 0, 30),

('success_criteria',
 'Success Criteria',
 'Success criteria are the specific, measurable outcomes the Economic Buyer needs to see to consider the purchase successful. Without agreed criteria, a POC has no end state — it runs indefinitely, or ends with an ambiguous "we need more time."',
 E'## Success Criteria\n\nA proof of concept without agreed success criteria is not an evaluation — it is an extended demo. The customer can always find one more thing to test, one more edge case to explore, one more stakeholder to involve. The founder waits, updates the product, runs more sessions, and eventually realises the evaluation has become a habit rather than a process.\n\nSuccess criteria end this. They define the specific outcomes that, if achieved, mean the purchase proceeds.\n\n### What good success criteria look like\n\nGood success criteria are:\n- **Specific**: "Reduce false positive rate below 5% on the test dataset" not "perform well"\n- **Measurable**: you both agree on how to measure it before the evaluation begins\n- **Time-bounded**: achieved by a specific date, not "when we''re ready"\n- **Owned**: the EB has agreed to them, not just the technical evaluator\n\nPoor success criteria: "We''ll know it when we see it."\n\n### When to establish them\n\nBefore the evaluation begins. If a customer asks for a POC before success criteria are established, the right response is: "Absolutely — let''s spend 30 minutes agreeing what success looks like first, so we''re both clear on what we''re measuring."\n\n### The success criteria conversation\n\nAsk: "If we run this evaluation and it goes perfectly, what specifically would you see that would make you confident to proceed?" Then: "Who needs to agree that those criteria have been met?" The answer to the second question often reveals additional stakeholders you had not identified.',
 'If this evaluation goes perfectly, what specifically would you see that would make you confident to move forward — and who needs to agree that those criteria have been met?',
 'The evaluation is underway with no written success criteria. The founder describes the goal as "to show the customer what the product can do." When asked what success looks like, the answer is vague or changes between conversations.',
 'Success criteria are documented and agreed in writing before the evaluation starts. The EB has signed off on them. There is a specific date for the evaluation review. Both parties have agreed on who has authority to declare the criteria met.',
 'A founder spent three months on a POC with a logistics company. The technical team was satisfied after six weeks. But there was no agreed endpoint, so the evaluation kept expanding — new datasets, new use cases, new stakeholders. When the founder finally pushed for a decision, the champion said they needed to loop in the head of operations, who had not been part of the evaluation. The head of operations asked for another two months. The founder had never established what "done" looked like, so there was no basis to say it was already done.',
 0, 40),

('next_action',
 'Next Action',
 'The next action is a specific, dated, mutually-agreed step that advances the deal. "Follow up next week" is not a next action. "Send the business case draft to Sarah by Thursday so she can review before the Friday leadership meeting" is a next action.',
 E'## Next Action\n\nEvery meeting, every call, every email exchange should end with a next action: a specific thing that will happen by a specific date, agreed by both parties. Without it, the deal drifts.\n\n### Why deals drift\n\nDeals drift when the next step is ambiguous or unowned. "We''ll be in touch" is the single most dangerous phrase in enterprise sales. It means the ball is in nobody''s court. The customer has other priorities. The founder waits, hoping for a response, not wanting to appear pushy. Two weeks pass. A month. The deal has not died — it has just become invisible.\n\n### What makes a good next action\n\n- **Who**: a named person (or people), not "the team"\n- **What**: a specific deliverable or meeting\n- **By when**: a specific date\n- **Why it matters**: linked to a step in the buying process\n\nExample: "I''ll send you the revised pricing by Wednesday. Can you confirm you''ll be able to share it with the CFO before the Thursday leadership meeting?"\n\n### The next action test\n\nAt the end of every customer interaction, ask yourself: "If I heard nothing from this customer for two weeks, would the deal still be on track?" If the answer is no, you need a next action that ensures something happens in less than two weeks.\n\n### Overdue next actions\n\nAn overdue next action is a signal, not just an admin failure. It means either the customer deprioritised the step (a buying signal worth investigating) or the founder did not have a genuine commitment from the customer. Both are worth understanding immediately.',
 'To keep things moving, what should happen next and by when — and can we put a date on it now?',
 'The next action is "follow up" or "check in" with no specific date or deliverable. Multiple next actions have been overdue for more than a week without investigation. The deal card shows the same next action it had two weeks ago.',
 'Every interaction ends with a specific next action, dated, agreed with the customer. Overdue actions are investigated within 48 hours. The next action always connects to a named step in the customer''s buying process.',
 'A founder had a great first meeting with a potential customer and left feeling confident. The agreed "next step" was to "think about the use cases and be in touch." The founder sent a follow-up email two days later. No response. Sent another a week later. No response. After three weeks, the founder discovered the contact had moved to a different team. There was no named next action, no date, and no backup contact. The deal was effectively dead after the first meeting.',
 0, 50),

-- ── TIER 1: Expansion concepts ───────────────────────────────────────────────

('expansion_motion',
 'The Expansion Motion',
 'Land-and-expand is the most common GTM motion for B2B AI companies, but "expand" is treated as something that happens naturally after a good POC. It doesn''t. Expansion is a separate sale, with a different buyer, a different business case, and a different process.',
 E'## The Expansion Motion\n\nMost enterprise sales teams celebrate the initial close and then wait. They wait for the customer to come back and ask for more. Sometimes this happens — usually slowly, usually late, usually at a smaller scale than the product justifies.\n\nThe expansion motion is the deliberate process of converting a successful initial deployment into a significantly larger commercial relationship. It is not automatic, and it is not driven by product quality alone.\n\n### Why expansion stalls\n\nThree structural reasons:\n\n**1. The POC champion is not the expansion Economic Buyer.** The person who championed the initial deployment is typically a technical lead or functional manager. The person who signs a 10× larger contract is typically a VP, a C-level executive, or a CFO. These are different people with different priorities, different relationships with the vendor, and different levels of awareness of what the pilot achieved.\n\n**2. There is no business case for the expansion.** The initial deal often closed on a combination of technical curiosity and champion enthusiasm. The expansion deal closes on documented ROI. If you did not establish success criteria upfront and measure against them, you have no business case to take to the expansion EB.\n\n**3. Nobody owns the expansion conversation.** Early-stage sales teams are focused on new logos. The customer success function (if it exists) is focused on retention. Nobody is explicitly responsible for driving expansion revenue, so nobody does it systematically.\n\n### The expansion as a parallel workstream\n\nThe expansion motion should begin before the initial deal closes. At the moment of close, three questions should be answered:\n1. What does a 10× version of this deal look like?\n2. Who would sign it?\n3. Have we met that person?\n\nThese are not hypothetical. They are the first steps of the next deal.',
 'Now that we''re moving forward — what does a much larger version of this relationship look like in 12 months, and who in your organisation would be involved in that decision?',
 'The deal is Won and the account has moved to "closed." No expansion vision is documented. No expansion EB has been named. The founder has not had a conversation about what growth looks like. The customer is being "managed" by whoever is handling onboarding.',
 'At close, the expansion vision is documented in one sentence. The expansion EB is named (even if not yet met). A milestone date is set for the first expansion conversation (typically 60–90 days post-deployment). The champion has been asked to facilitate an introduction to the expansion EB.',
 'A technical founder closed a 6-month pilot with a retail company at £40k. The pilot was technically successful — the model outperformed the benchmark by 30%. Eighteen months later, the relationship was still at £40k/year. The expansion had never happened because nobody had ever had the conversation. The champion had moved to a different role. The person now responsible for the function had never met the founder. The 30% performance improvement had never been translated into a business case. The £40k deal that should have become a £400k deal was renewed at £40k.',
 1, 10),

('expansion_eb',
 'The Expansion Economic Buyer',
 'The person who signs a large expansion contract is almost never the same person who championed the initial pilot. Identifying and meeting the expansion EB before the initial deal closes is one of the highest-leverage acts in enterprise sales.',
 E'## The Expansion Economic Buyer\n\nThe expansion EB exists at a different level of the organisation than the initial champion. A pilot signed by a Head of Data Science may expand to a contract signed by a CTO or CFO. A departmental deployment may expand to an enterprise-wide agreement signed by a COO.\n\n### How to identify the expansion EB\n\nAsk your champion: "If we wanted to expand this to [3×, 10×, the whole company], who would need to approve that level of investment?" The answer gives you the expansion EB. Follow up: "Have they heard about the pilot? Would it make sense to keep them informed as we go through the evaluation?"\n\nThe second question is strategic. Getting the expansion EB informed during the pilot — not necessarily involved, just informed — means that when the expansion conversation happens, they are not hearing about you for the first time.\n\n### The intro during the pilot\n\nThe best time to meet the expansion EB is during a successful moment of the pilot: when you have hit a milestone, when early results are strong, when there is something positive to share. Ask your champion: "Would it make sense to give [EB name] a quick update on how the pilot is going? Just a 20-minute briefing — I can put together a one-pager." Most champions will agree. Most expansion EBs appreciate being kept informed.\n\n### What to say to the expansion EB in the pilot\n\nNot a pitch. A briefing. "The pilot is progressing well. We''re on track to [hit success criteria]. I wanted to make sure you had visibility before the review meeting. Can I ask — from your perspective, what would need to be true for this to expand beyond the initial scope?"',
 'If the initial pilot goes well and we wanted to expand significantly, who in your organisation would be the right person to involve in that conversation?',
 'The deal is Won and the expansion EB has never been named. The founder only knows the champion. There is no plan for how to reach the expansion EB. The champion is expected to "handle the internal process" without any founder involvement.',
 'The expansion EB is named before the initial deal closes. The founder has had at least one direct interaction — even a brief email introduction — during the pilot. The expansion EB is aware of the pilot outcomes and has expressed some view on what growth would look like.',
 'A founder closed a successful pilot with an insurance company. The champion was a Principal Data Scientist who had driven the evaluation. At close, the founder asked about expansion and the champion said "let''s get the pilot running first." Twelve months later, the champion left the company. The new Head of Data Science had never heard of the product. The expansion EB — the Chief Actuary — had also never heard of it. The founder had to restart the sales process from scratch. A single introductory email to the Chief Actuary during the pilot would have created the continuity that the champion''s departure severed.',
 1, 20),

-- ── TIER 2: MEDDPICC concepts ────────────────────────────────────────────────

('meddpicc_metrics',
 'Metrics',
 'Metrics are the specific, quantified measures by which the Economic Buyer will judge whether the purchase was successful. Without agreed metrics, there is no business case — only a hope that the product will be useful.',
 E'## Metrics\n\nThe M in MEDDPICC is the quantified value your product delivers, expressed in terms the Economic Buyer cares about. This is the foundation of the business case.\n\n### Why metrics matter\n\nAn EB who approves a significant purchase needs to be able to answer one question from their CFO or board: "Why did we spend this money?" The answer requires a number — or ideally, a ratio. "We deployed this product and it reduced manual review time by 60%, saving approximately £400k/year against a cost of £120k" is an answer. "We deployed this product and the team finds it very useful" is not.\n\n### Types of metrics\n\n**Hard metrics** (preferred): revenue increase, cost reduction, headcount avoided, time saved × salary, error rate reduction × cost of errors, churn reduction × LTV.\n\n**Soft metrics** (acceptable as secondary): risk reduction, compliance improvement, decision speed, employee satisfaction.\n\n### Who provides the metrics\n\nYou frame the model; the customer provides the numbers. Ask: "What is the current cost of [the problem you solve]?" or "How many hours per week does your team spend on [the task]?" Then apply your known improvement rate to their numbers.\n\n### When metrics are weak\n\nA deal that cannot be supported by at least one hard metric is a deal that depends entirely on champion enthusiasm. Champion enthusiasm does not survive budget scrutiny. Establish the metrics before the proposal, or the proposal will stall at the first EB question.',
 'Help me understand the current cost of this problem — in time, headcount, or direct cost — so we can frame what the improvement is worth.',
 'The business case uses phrases like "significant ROI" or "major efficiency gains" without numbers. When asked for the metric, the champion says "it''s hard to quantify." The founder has not asked for the data needed to calculate impact.',
 'The business case includes at least one hard metric with the customer''s own numbers: current state, improvement expected, value of improvement. The EB has seen and accepted the metric framing.',
 'A founder presented a proposal to a manufacturing company with a business case that said the product would "dramatically improve quality control." The procurement team asked for the ROI calculation. The founder could not provide specific numbers because they had never asked the customer for the data. The proposal was sent back for revision. By the time a revised version was ready, the budget cycle had closed.',
 2, 10),

('meddpicc_champion',
 'Champion',
 'A champion is not someone who likes your product. A champion is someone who will actively sell it internally on your behalf, stake their reputation on the outcome, and tell you when things are going wrong. Most people founders call champions are sponsors. The difference is critical.',
 E'## Champion\n\nThe champion is your internal advocate — the person inside the customer organisation who wants you to win and will work to make it happen. They are not just enthusiastic about the product; they are invested in the outcome.\n\n### Champion vs. Sponsor\n\nA **sponsor** introduces you to people, attends meetings, and says positive things when asked. They are useful but passive.\n\nA **champion** proactively arranges meetings you didn''t ask for, warns you when something is about to go wrong internally, crafts the internal narrative, and pushes back on obstacles on your behalf. They have skin in the game — their recommendation is on the line.\n\n### How to identify a real champion\n\nA real champion will do four things:\n1. Tell you when the deal is at risk, even when it reflects badly on them\n2. Arrange meetings with people you have not yet met — including the EB\n3. Give you the internal business case language the organisation actually uses\n4. Coach you on how to navigate the internal politics\n\n### The champion test\n\nAsk your champion to arrange a meeting with the EB. A real champion will do it, even if it takes time. A sponsor will say "I''ll mention it" and then not follow up.\n\n### What weakens champions\n\nChampions lose influence when they change roles, when their initiatives are deprioritised, or when they over-promise internally and cannot deliver. A champion who has told their leadership "this will definitely work" and then faces a difficult evaluation is a champion under pressure. Keep them informed and give them wins they can report.',
 'If you were going to recommend this internally, what would you say — and who would you say it to?',
 'The "champion" only communicates through scheduled demo calls. They have never proactively shared information, warned about internal obstacles, or arranged a meeting you didn''t ask for. When asked about internal dynamics, they give generic answers.',
 'The champion has arranged at least one meeting with a stakeholder the founder did not know existed. They have warned the founder about at least one internal obstacle. They have shared internal language or framing that the founder used to reposition the proposal.',
 'A founder had a champion who attended every meeting, nodded enthusiastically, and said "I''m fully behind this." When the proposal went to the leadership team, the champion presented it without telling the founder, got one objection they couldn''t answer, and reported back that "there are some concerns about integration complexity." The founder had never heard this objection before because the champion had never surfaced it. A real champion would have told the founder about the integration concern weeks earlier and the two of them would have built a response together.',
 2, 40),

('meddpicc_decision_criteria',
 'Decision Criteria',
 'Decision criteria are the formal and informal standards by which the customer will evaluate competing options. Understanding them tells you whether you are being measured on your strengths or your weaknesses.',
 E'## Decision Criteria\n\nEvery customer has a set of criteria they use to decide between vendors. Some are explicit (written into an RFP or evaluation framework). Some are implicit (the CTO always cares about SOC 2 compliance; the head of engineering always asks about API design). Your job is to surface them all and influence them before they are set in stone.\n\n### Formal vs. informal criteria\n\n**Formal criteria** appear in RFPs, evaluation scorecards, and vendor comparison documents. They are the stated basis for decision.\n\n**Informal criteria** are the unstated preferences that often drive the actual decision. "We''ve had bad experiences with US-only vendors." "The board wants to see us using UK-based AI providers." "The CTO trained at Google and has strong views on API design."\n\n### How to influence criteria\n\nCriteria are most malleable early in the evaluation — before the customer has talked to multiple vendors. The questions you ask shape the criteria: "Have you thought about how you''d evaluate ongoing model accuracy?" introduces a criterion that may favour you if your monitoring capabilities are strong.\n\n### When criteria work against you\n\nIf you discover that the decision criteria include something you do poorly, you have two options: reframe the criterion ("latency matters less when you have batch processing") or accept that this deal is not winnable on this evaluation. Do not pretend the criterion does not exist.',
 'How are you thinking about comparing different options — what are the two or three things that matter most to the decision?',
 'The founder does not know the formal evaluation criteria. The decision criteria have been set without the founder''s input. The customer is running a formal RFP that was written before any vendor conversation.',
 'The founder knows both the formal and informal criteria. At least one criterion has been influenced by the founder''s framing. The founder knows which criteria favour them and which do not.',
 'A founder discovered three weeks into a formal evaluation that the customer had a strict requirement for on-premise deployment — a criterion that had been in the evaluation framework from day one. The founder''s product was cloud-only. The criterion had never been discussed because the founder had never asked about the evaluation framework. The deal was unwinnable.',
 3, 10),

('meddpicc_decision_process',
 'Decision Process',
 'The decision process is the sequence of steps, approvals, and stakeholders that lead from "we''ve chosen a vendor" to "the contract is signed." Not knowing the process means not knowing when or why the deal might stall.',
 E'## Decision Process\n\nEnterprise buying decisions do not happen in a single moment. They move through a sequence of steps: technical evaluation, internal recommendation, business case approval, legal review, procurement, contract negotiation, final sign-off. Each step involves different people and can take different amounts of time.\n\n### Why technical founders underestimate this\n\nFounders who have been technical buyers know how long it takes to evaluate a product. They are less familiar with what happens after the technical decision is made — and this is where deals most often stall or die. A CFO who did not know about the purchase until it reached their approval queue is not going to approve it in 48 hours.\n\n### Mapping the decision process\n\nAsk your champion: "Walk me through what needs to happen internally from where we are today to a signed contract. Who needs to approve at each step, and how long does each step typically take?"\n\nThen ask: "Has anything like this gone through this process before? How long did it take?"\n\nThe answer to the second question is the most reliable predictor of your actual close date.\n\n### Common process surprises\n\n- Legal review: 2–8 weeks in most enterprises, especially for AI contracts with data processing implications\n- Procurement: may require a competitive bid process even if you are the preferred vendor\n- Board approval: any contract above a threshold may require board sign-off, which only happens at quarterly meetings\n- Security review: especially relevant for AI products handling sensitive data',
 'Help me understand the internal process from here to a signed contract — who needs to be involved at each step, and what are the typical timelines?',
 'The founder does not know the steps between the current stage and a signed contract. The expected close date is based on the champion''s optimism, not on a mapped process. Legal, procurement, and security reviews have not been discussed.',
 'The founder has a documented map of the approval process: who approves at each step, estimated time per step, and whether any steps can run in parallel. The expected close date reflects this process, not wishful thinking.',
 'A founder was told by their champion that "we should be able to close this by end of quarter." The founder built their forecast around this. Two weeks before quarter end, the champion mentioned that all contracts above £50k required a procurement tender process. The deal took four more months. The founder''s forecast was wrong not because the customer changed their mind, but because the process had never been mapped.',
 3, 20),

('meddpicc_paper_process',
 'Paper Process',
 'The paper process is everything that happens between a verbal yes and a signed contract: legal review, security assessment, procurement tender, DPA negotiation, MSA redlines. Technical founders consistently underestimate how long this takes.',
 E'## Paper Process\n\nA verbal commitment from the Economic Buyer is not a closed deal. Between "yes" and a signed contract, most enterprise organisations have a sequence of administrative and legal steps that can take weeks or months. The paper process maps these.\n\n### What the paper process includes\n\n**Legal review**: Most enterprises have in-house legal counsel or outside counsel who review vendor contracts. For AI products, the review often includes data processing terms, liability clauses, IP ownership, and model training provisions. This is not quick.\n\n**Data Processing Agreement (DPA)**: Required under GDPR for any product that processes personal data. Your DPA needs to be reviewed and often negotiated. If you don''t have a DPA ready, that adds time.\n\n**Master Service Agreement (MSA)**: Large enterprises often want to sign on their paper (their standard MSA) rather than yours. Negotiating from their MSA takes longer than negotiating from yours.\n\n**Security review**: Many enterprises require a formal vendor security assessment — questionnaires, penetration test reports, SOC 2 reports, sometimes on-site reviews. For AI products, they may also ask about model training data provenance.\n\n**Procurement**: If the purchase exceeds a threshold, it may require a competitive tender or formal procurement process, even if you are the preferred vendor.\n\n### Starting paper early\n\nDo not wait until after the technical evaluation to start legal and procurement. As soon as you have a verbal indication that the customer is serious, ask: "While we finalise the technical evaluation, should we get legal and procurement introduced to our teams so they can start reviewing the standard documents?" Most procurement teams are happy to start early. Most in-house lawyers are too.',
 'While we''re completing the evaluation, it would be worth understanding your internal process for contracts — does legal need to review our standard terms, or do you work from your own MSA?',
 'The paper process has not been discussed. There is no contact with legal or procurement. The deal is at Closing stage but the founder does not know how long legal review takes at this organisation.',
 'The founder has identified the legal and procurement contacts. Standard contract documents (MSA, DPA, order form) have been shared with the customer''s legal team. Any known redline preferences have been surfaced. There are no surprises expected in the paper process.',
 'A founder closed the commercial negotiation with a healthcare company in mid-November with an expectation of signing "before the end of the year." They had never spoken to the customer''s legal team. Legal review started in late November and immediately surfaced issues with the AI model liability clause and the data processing agreement. The legal teams negotiated through December. The contract was not signed until late January — past the customer''s budget cycle, which meant the funding had to be re-approved. The deal almost died.',
 3, 30),

('meddpicc_competition',
 'Competition',
 'Understanding the competitive landscape means knowing who else is in the evaluation, what they are good at, and what your champion thinks about them. Not knowing this means you cannot differentiate or counter-position.',
 E'## Competition\n\nEvery enterprise evaluation involves a competitive dimension — even if it is just the option to do nothing, build internally, or stay with the incumbent. Understanding the competition means understanding what you are being compared to and on what basis.\n\n### Types of competition\n\n**Direct competitors**: Other vendors with similar products being actively evaluated.\n\n**Incumbent/build**: The current approach (whether a third-party tool, an internal system, or a manual process). This is often the strongest competitor because it requires no new purchasing decision.\n\n**"Do nothing"**: The option to defer. This is more common in challenging budget environments and is often underestimated as a competitive threat.\n\n### How to surface the competitive situation\n\nAsk your champion: "Are you looking at other options alongside us?" Most champions will tell you. Follow up: "What have you heard about [competitor]?" and "What does [competitor] do well that we''d need to match or exceed in your view?"\n\n### Counter-positioning\n\nYou do not need to attack competitors. You need to shift the decision criteria toward your strengths. If a competitor is stronger on feature X but you are stronger on outcome Y, work to make outcome Y the primary criterion. The question "what matters more to you, feature X or outcome Y?" is more effective than "here''s why feature X is actually not that important."\n\n### The build vs. buy question\n\nFor AI products specifically, the "we could build this ourselves" objection is common. The right response is not to argue that building is hard (they know it is possible). The right response is to calculate the total cost: engineering time × salary × opportunity cost of not building something else, plus ongoing maintenance. Most builds are more expensive than they appear.',
 'Are you looking at other options alongside us — and what are the things they do that you find most compelling?',
 'The founder does not know who else is in the evaluation. The champion says "we''re just looking at you" but the founder has not verified this. The founder cannot articulate what a competitor would say they do better.',
 'The founder knows which vendors are in the evaluation and what each is positioning on. The decision criteria have been shaped to favour the founder''s differentiated strengths. The champion has been coached on how to counter the primary competitive objection.',
 'A founder was told by their champion "you''re the only vendor we''re seriously considering." In the final presentation, a procurement team member mentioned "the other shortlisted vendor" by name — a competitor the founder had never heard of, who had apparently been in the evaluation for two months. The founder had no competitive positioning prepared and could not address the comparison. The deal was lost to the competitor.',
 3, 50),

('champion_vs_sponsor',
 'Champion vs. Sponsor',
 'The distinction between a champion and a sponsor is one of the most important concepts in enterprise selling — and the one most often confused. Getting it wrong means you spend months with false confidence.',
 E'## Champion vs. Sponsor\n\nThis is a nuanced distinction that experienced enterprise salespeople make instinctively and that most founders never learn. Getting it wrong means you believe you have a champion, proceed with confidence, and then discover at a critical moment that your "champion" did not have the influence or the commitment you assumed.\n\n### The sponsor\n\nA sponsor is an executive or manager who:\n- Is willing to meet with you\n- Has access to the Economic Buyer\n- Speaks positively about your product when asked\n- Introduces you to others when directly asked\n- Does not take initiative on your behalf\n\nSponsors are valuable. They are not champions.\n\n### The champion\n\nA champion is someone who:\n- Proactively advocates for you when you are not in the room\n- Takes initiative — arranges meetings without being asked, forwards your materials, coaches you on internal politics\n- Has personal stake in the outcome — their recommendation is on the line\n- Tells you when things are going wrong, even when it''s uncomfortable\n- Has genuine influence over the Economic Buyer or the decision process\n\n### The crucial test\n\nAsk your "champion" to arrange a meeting with the EB without you suggesting who the EB is. A champion who has real access and real commitment will make it happen. A sponsor will say they''ll try and then nothing will happen.\n\n### Why founders misidentify sponsors as champions\n\nSponsors are positive, engaged, and validating. They make founders feel the deal is progressing well. Founders want to believe the deal is progressing well. The result is a systematic overestimation of champion strength.',
 'If you were to recommend us internally at the next leadership meeting — without me in the room — what would you say, and who would be in that room?',
 'The "champion" has not initiated any action on the founder''s behalf. All meetings have been arranged by the founder. The champion does not share internal information proactively. The founder has never been warned about an internal obstacle.',
 'The champion has proactively arranged at least one meeting, shared internal information the founder did not ask for, and warned the founder about at least one obstacle or competing priority. The champion can speak credibly about what the EB cares about.',
 'A founder had an enthusiastic point of contact at a media company who attended every demo, brought colleagues along, and consistently said "I love what you''re building." When asked to arrange a meeting with the VP of Engineering, the contact said "I''ll see what I can do." Three weeks later, nothing had happened. The founder eventually discovered that the contact was a Principal Engineer with no relationship with the VP. They were a sponsor — a genuine enthusiast with no internal pull.',
 2, 30);
